western visual novels are commonly contrasted with "eastern visual novels", which are mainly produced in japan. "visual novel" (ビジュアルノベル bijuaru noberu) is a phrase created in japan to refer to narrative games that involve written dialog, character artwork and fixed background art, sometimes with animation, video insertions and soundtracks. the term is often used in topics or comments by game-players discussing the rising number of non-japanese visual novels produced in the west. the game media often refer to the terms western developed visual novels  or western made visual novels. the visual novel is a mixed-media novel genre that became popular in western countries among anime fans who in the 1990s discovered visual novel games derived from their favorite anime, often unofficially translated by fansub teams without authorization and distributed free on the internet. then original visual novel games began to be created by non-japanese creators.